name: Co-Learning Day
short_desc: We are a group of people interested in learning programming in a collaborative social context. The model for this group derived from our experience during Hackership. We were inspired by all the things that we learned and the new perspectives we gained. But we also knew that we wouldn't have the same environment at home, and we thought "Ugh, back to learning in isolation!" Coworking spaces and user groups don't really make the difference for us. So in talking about this, we found that we felt the same way, and came up with the idea of meeting up for continuous learning in a friendly group. Here's the idea: - Meet every 2 weeks for 1 whole day. - We meet in a place where we can sit together. - We start with a coworking space. In the morning, we talk briefly about what we want to learn, so that small groups can form. - We spend the day with self directed learning. We help each other in case we get stuck. - Over coffee breaks and lunch there is opportunity to chat. - In the evening we reserve 20 minutes for presentations, aka lightning talks. Anybody can talk about what the person thinks might be interesting to the others (this is different from Hackership). The aim is to create a friendly group with diverse skills and skill levels.

name: Tech In NYC
short_desc:
We're a bunch of software developers, designers and engineers who love technology and are tired of working all day. We're here for two reasons:

1. Mentorship

The tech scene in NYC does not foster real relationships and/or a sense of helping. As a recruiter, I hear it a lot. Either the candidates are junior and don't know what they're doing, don't know where to apply to (end up applying everywhere), or are too picky although their backgrounds in tech don't justify it. We want to foster a community where we pair up beginner and more seasoned developers and engineers to encourage feedback and personal development. 

2. Hanging Out

I worked at a few startups and I didn't have any free time for the life of me. This group is just to get together, grab some drinks, and talk about technology. Because that's who we are, a bunch of technology-seeking maniacs. 

We're crazed about the Toptal blog announcing a new framework, or about Apple Watch SDK or for that guy who wants to talk about how awesome his tech stack is. We can't wait for the future to be fully tech'd out because we'll be at the forefront of it.

name: Santa Cruz JavaScript
short_desc: We want to open up our ongoing informal hack/code sessions to everyone, and encourage others to join in and replicate this behavior. The format is simple: we pick some sort of venue (coffee shop, office area, lounge, or even a wine bar), make the announcement, and hope that members come. If you're familiar with the LinkedIn Hack Night (graciously hosted by BayNode's Adam Crabtree), members show up, find an allocated table, sit with unfamiliar or familiar faces, and do whatever they feel like in the JS-inspired environment. This is a great opportunity to participate in a mini-lab of sorts within casual environments, where it is most likely that you will learn something new w/ JS (framework, library, debugging strategies, etc.), meet cool people, get some stuff done, showcase your project, and the like.
